Exercise 5 -

Below I have created billboard_numeric. Your goal now is to run a p value matrix using the custom cor.mtest function (and save it into an object called b_pvalues).

#Run this chunk as-is and do not make any changes
cor.mtest <- function(mat, ...) {
    mat <- as.matrix(mat)
    n <- ncol(mat)
    p.mat<- matrix(NA, n, n)
    diag(p.mat) <- 0
    for (i in 1:(n - 1)) {
        for (j in (i + 1):n) {
            tmp <- cor.test(mat[, i], mat[, j], ...)
            p.mat[i, j] <- p.mat[j, i] <- tmp$p.value
        }
    }
  colnames(p.mat) <- rownames(p.mat) <- colnames(mat)
  p.mat
}
billboard_numeric <- billboard %>%
  select(spotify_track_duration_ms, danceability, energy, loudness,
         acousticness, liveness, valence, tempo, spotify_track_popularity) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  cor()

#code goes here
b_pvalues <- cor.mtest(billboard_numeric)

Your final exercise in this correlation exercise is to edit the below correlation matrix plot using the corrplot library.

Make sure you: 1. Set the corrgram to âupperâ to display only the upper triangular of the correlation matrix 2. Hide the correlation coefficients on the principal diagonal by adding: diag=FALSE 3. Set p.mat = b_pvalues, sig.level = 0.05, insig = "pch", addCoef.col = "black", tl.col="black", and tl.srt=45

library(corrplot)
corrplot(billboard_numeric, type = "upper", diag = FALSE, 
         p.mat = b_pvalues, sig.level = 0.05, insig = "pch",
         addCoef.col = "black", tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 45)

In order to run a t-test, our grouping variable (State) can only have two levels. We currently have 50. Below I am creating a new dataset called state_nurses that we will use only in this exercise and exercise 8. Fill in and replace âSTATE ONEâ and âSTATE TWOâ with the two states you selected.

state_nurses <- nurses %>%
  filter(State == "California" | 
           State == "Arizona") 

state_nurses$State <- droplevels(state_nurses$State)

Now you run your t-test. Your goal is to test if there is a significant difference in Hourly Wage Avg based on the states you selected. Interpret the t-test results.

t.test(`Hourly Wage Avg` ~ State, data = state_nurses)

Exercise 8 -

Below I have created a basic ggplot code chunk to observe the differences. Your task is to improve the graph by: Cleaning up all of the labels, adding a title, make each bar a different color, and add a theme. See https://ggplot2-book.org/polishing.html for a list of included themes. Finally, interpret what you see.

library(scales)
ggplot(state_nurses, aes(State, `Hourly Wage Avg`, fill = State)) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "bar") +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +
  labs(x = "State", y = "Mean Hourly Wage", title = "Hourly Nurse Wage for Arizona vs California ") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format())
